Reflection - Language-Based Music Tagging

1. What surprised me:

One of the most interesting findings was how far text alone could go in describing music.

Captions often implicitly encode:
Genre (“rock”, “jazz”)
Mood (“calm”, “energetic”)
Instrumentation (“guitar”, “piano”)

Despite no audio input, the model achieved meaningful performance, indicating that:

Natural language descriptions act as compressed semantic representations of audio.

However, performance varied heavily depending on:

Caption richness
Annotator subjectivity
Vocabulary diversity




2. Where classical ML struggled:

Even with careful engineering, LinearSVC + TF-IDF showed clear limitations:

1. No semantic understanding
“happy melody” vs “joyful tune” treated as unrelated
Synonyms are not captured
2. Weak long-range context
Cannot model relationships across phrases
N-grams are shallow approximations
3. Label imbalance sensitivity
Rare tags had near-zero F1
Even with class_weight="balanced", performance was unstable
4. Multi-label complexity
Labels are correlated (e.g., rock → guitar)
Model treats each independently
5. Vocabulary brittleness

From your robustness test:

Reducing TF-IDF features caused noticeable degradation
Shows over-reliance on surface-level tokens




3. What improved robustness revealed

Your experiments were very strong signals of maturity:

Reduced Vocabulary Test
Performance drop → model depends on lexical coverage
Indicates lack of abstraction
Label Dropout Simulation
Model degraded under noisy supervision
Shows sensitivity to missing annotations

Insight:

The system is not inherently robust—it relies heavily on clean, dense labeling.




4. What would improve this system
 1. Audio Features (Biggest Upgrade)

Adding features like:

MFCCs
Spectrogram embeddings
Tempo / rhythm features

Would:

Capture actual sound characteristics
Reduce dependence on noisy text
 2. Transformer Models (Major Leap)

Replacing TF-IDF + SVM with:

BERT / sentence transformers

Would:

Capture semantics
Understand synonyms
Improve generalization
3. Larger & richer corpora

More data would:

Improve rare label learning
Stabilize multi-label predictions
Reduce overfitting to vocabulary
4. Label dependency modeling

Using:

Classifier chains
Graph-based models

Would:

Capture relationships between tags




Final Takeaway

This project demonstrated that classical ML can provide a strong baseline for multi-label music tagging, but true scalability and semantic understanding require moving beyond bag-of-words representations toward multimodal and deep learning approaches.
